  "notes": [
    {
      "id": "note_8",
      "text": "Plots one or more phase/angle columns (e.g. acrophases, activity onsets) as points around a clock face on an adjustable period, each column a coloured group with its Rayleigh mean-resultant vector — the arrow's length is R (0 = dispersed, 1 = tightly clustered) (Batschelet 1981). Wiring an optional time column to a series turns it into a value-radius clock plot instead: each row is placed at its time-of-day with radius proportional to its value, and the vector becomes an amplitude-weighted acrophase. Toggle rose wedges for a circular histogram of an untimed group, or the Watson-Williams test (the circular analogue of one-way ANOVA) to ask whether untimed groups share a common mean direction (Watson & Williams 1956) — timed series sit outside that comparison, since WW compares discrete event angles, not a continuous weighted rhythm. The demo shows both modes: two untimed onset-phase groups (near 7 h and 19 h) with a significant Watson-Williams test, plus a timed activity series rendered as a value-radius clock.",
      "x": 40,
      "y": 24,
      "width": 360,
      "height": 190
    }
